{{page-title "Documentation — Resumes"}}
<div class="container mx-auto max-w-3xl py-6 px-4 space-y-6">

  <Panel::Card>
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">Resumes</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      Resumes in Career Caddy are structured records of your work history — not just PDF uploads.
      Each resume stores your experiences, education, skills, certifications, and projects as
      individual editable items. This structured form gives the AI richer context than a flat document.
    </p>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of the resumes list" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Import vs. Build Manually</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-1">Import (PDF or DOCX)</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
          Upload your existing resume file and Career Caddy will parse it into structured
          sections. Review and clean up the extracted data before saving. This is the fastest
          way to get started if you already have a polished resume.
        </p>
        {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of the resume import form with file upload" /> --}}
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-1">Build Section by Section</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
          Add experiences, education, skills, certifications, and projects one at a time.
          More work upfront, but gives you the cleanest structured data.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">How Resumes Feed the AI</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-3">
      Resume content supplements your Career Data when generating scores, cover letters,
      and summaries. If your Career Data describes your voice and goals, your resume provides
      the specifics: exact dates, company names, technologies, and achievements.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      You can have multiple resumes (different versions for different role types) and link
      the appropriate one to each job application.
    </p>
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Example Resume</h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded p-4 text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-2">
      <div><span class="font-semibold">Title:</span> Senior Backend Engineer — General</div>
      <div><span class="font-semibold">Name on resume:</span> Alex Rivera</div>
      <div class="pt-1 space-y-1">
        <div class="font-semibold">Experiences (3):</div>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-600 pl-2 space-y-1">
          <li>Lead Backend Engineer at Meridian Health (2021–present)</li>
          <li>Software Engineer at CartPulse (2018–2021)</li>
          <li>Junior Developer at Sunrise Labs (2016–2018)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="pt-1 space-y-1">
        <div class="font-semibold">Education (1):</div>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-600 pl-2">
          <li>B.S. Computer Science, UT Austin, 2017</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of a resume detail page" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

</div>
